postcontent: brand-new, unfired, IWI USA TAVOR SAR-B16, .223/5.56 NATO Bull Pup Carbine. The TAVOR is a perfect fusion of an ordnance grade steel receiver coupled to a Mil-Spec cold hammer forged barrel and encased into a high-impact strength polymer uni-body with exceptional situational ergonomics. The ultra-compact form factor allows for easy transitions in close quarter situations…or even in your favorite deer blind. The bullpup design moves the center of gravity of the rifle closer to the users’ body allowing for more instinctive aiming and improved acquisition time to target. title: For Sale:  Vintage Marbles Ideal Hunting Knife
postcontent:
Up for sale is a very vintage Marbles Ideal Hunting Knife. Overall length is 12" with a 7 1/2" blade. As far as I can determine (based on the left-pointing serif in the "Marbles" stamping) this knife dates from late 1919 to the early 1930's. The blade is clean, no knicks, and carries a wonderful old patina. My research tells me that this knife was probably made with an early version of 1095 carbon steel. The sheath is almost certainly not original to the knife; it has a USN stamp on it and is in fairly rough condition.

FTF sale in Brownsburg, no shipping.

title: For Sale:  GUN is SOLD...AMMO available for sale...Arcus 2 Tone 9mm
location: Also .357 38 ammo for sale, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
The Arcus 98DA is a full-size, BROWNING CLONE, used my many governments, police agencies , military around the world. It features a short-recoil, locked-breech pistol chambered in 9×19 Parabellum with a frame, slide and barrel CNC machined from steel forgings. The sample gun featured stippled rubber grips that provide a very slip-resistant surface that will help prevent this solid piece from squirming out of your hand. The matte blue finish, while not fine, is evenly applied, and there were no sharp edges on the gun.

Thumb safeties are seeing a resurgence of popularity, and the Arcus 98DA comes so equipped. This feature, when combined with the gun’s automatic firing-pin safety, allows the gun to be carried either cocked-and-locked or with the hammer down on a loaded chamber, but extreme caution must be exercised when lowering the hammer since there is no decocker. Because the thumb safety cannot be engaged with the hammer down, there is no third option. The magazine release, located behind the triggerguard, worked properly, and when pushed, magazines dropped free like a 500-pounder from a B-17. Reloads were easy because the narrow snout of the double-stack magazine is slipped readily into the wide magazine well. The Arcus also has a lanyard ring, another practical feature from the past that is regaining popularity.

Disassembly of the Arcus 98DA is like that of a Browning Hi-Power, the design on which the Arcus is based. The slide is first locked to the rear by engaging the safety, not the slide catch, in a takedown notch. The slide catch is then pushed up and to the left to remove it, which allows the slide to be taken from the frame. Last, the barrel, recoil spring and guide rod are separated. An interesting design feature is a deep recess at the front of the barrel lug that positively engages the rear of the recoil-spring guide. The guide also contains a spring-loaded ball that fits a retaining detent in the slide catch shaft to prevent the slide catch from creeping to the left

title: For Sale:  Glock 20 (10mm)
postcontent:
I have for sale a Gen3 Glock 20SF with 3 mags. The gun is very lightly used and in like new condition. 10mm is an awesome caliber- it is as powerful as the .357Mag but since it's a semi-auto you get 15+1 rounds instead of only 5 or 6. I bought this gun new a little over a year ago and have put just 105 rounds through it. It will come in the original case with all the original paperwork and all the original Glock accessories like the cleaning tools and the magazine loader. The gun is equipped with a right-handed Clipdraw which was professionally installed at Diamondback Police Supply. This gun also comes with a Saf-T-Blok so that it can be carried cocked (technically half-cocked) with little worry of accidental discharge. The gun also comes with a trigger lock.

This gun has never failed to feed or eject and has never malfunctioned in any way, shape, or form. It has always been properly and thoroughly cleaned after firing. The trigger internals were polished last year and I'm pretty sure I haven't fired it since. Except for a few trips to the range this gun has spent its entire life in the safe. I bought it with the intention of carrying it but I changed my mind and since I don't shoot much any more I've decided to sell it. 

About the SF: I have fairly large hands- I'm 6' and around 250lbs- but I went with the SF because when I compared the 20 and the 20SF side by side I felt that while both frames were fine size-wise the differently contoured backstrap of the SF caused my hand to line up closer to the middle of the gun making it balance better in my hand. The SF also let me keep my wrist straighter which felt more natural to me, more like the grip angle of a 1911.

I am asking $600 for this gun and all its accessories plus about 15 rounds of defensive ammo. The price is firm and I am not looking for any advice about it. I will only sell face to face in Tucson, AZ. If you are interested or have any questions please email me and I will get back to you shortly. My schedule right now is mostly open so if you want to see or buy the gun I should be able to meet up with you fairly quickly.
